@subsection Requirements
GNU remotecontrol can run anywhere that can run PHP with cURL and MySQL.  Follow the requirements stated by the Web Server application you so choose to use.

GNU remotecontrol runs without any known problems on @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_HTTP_Server,Apache} and @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_Information_Services,IIS}.  Running GNU remotecontrol on a @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_lightweight_web_servers,lighweight} Web Server versus a @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_web_servers,complete} Web Server is possible, but not recommended.  This is due to the security benefits of a complete Web Server.  Again, you are responsible for setting up your security on your Web Server.

@subsection Configuration
Follow the configuration stated by the Web Server application you so choose to use.

Here is what you need for running GNU remotecontrol on Apache, after you setup your security on your Web Server.

	@itemize @bullet
	@item
	@strong{Apache httpd.config:}
	
	Options FollowSymLinks
	 
	AllowOverride None
	
	Order allow,deny
	Allow from all
	
	AuthType Digest
	
	AuthName "tstat"
	
	AuthUserFile "PATH_TO.../passwords_digest"
	
	Require user GNU remotecontrol
	
	

	@item
	@strong{Settings necessary in your PHP configuration (php.ini):}
	
	register_globals = Off
	
	auto_globals_jit = On
	
	

	@item
	@strong{Extensions necessary in your PHP installation:}
	
	php_curl
	
	php_mysqli
    @end itemize


