@section Nagios Plugins
We have developed 2 plugins to round out the GNU remotecontrol Architecture.  The outcome of these plugins is to capture numbers related to your IP enabled thermostat and RSS feeds for weather information out of doors.  Numbers are so much easier for processing data to achieve knowledge.  Text, images, video, and so on are on quite complicated to process into knowledge.  The metrics of @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temperature,Temperature}, @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humidity,Humidity}, @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wind_speed,Wind Speed}, @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wind_chill,Wind Chill}, and @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barometric_pressure,Atmospheric (Barometric) Pressure} fit into the rapid processing of HVAC data into knowledge with light speed.  Certainly other metrics can be added in as preferred, as shared below.

Please review the source code for each of these plugins to see detailed instruction for proper usage.  The following is an outline of the detailed instruction.

@subsection Thermostat Plugin - check_ubicom
This plugin will attempt to read temperature and humidity from an IP thermostat.   Successful reads initially set the response to @code{STATE_OK}.  If the temperature or  humidity falls outside the range set by the @code{warn-temperature} or the  @code{warn-humidity} arguments, then the response is upgraded to @code{STATE_WARNING}.  If the temperature or humidity falls outside the range set by the @code{critical-temperature} or the @code{critical-humidity} arguments, then the response is further upgraded to @code{STATE_CRITICAL}.  Failure to read both values (due to timeout or parsing failure) results in a @code{STATE_UNKNOWN} response.

Temperature and humidity arguments may specify a minimum, a maximum, or both.   A ':' character must be used to follow a minimum or precede a maximum.  For example.....


@subsubsection Syntax Example - IMPERIAL

@emph{check_ubicom -wt :70 -ct :90 -wh 10: -ch 5: -t 60 -I example.remote-mon.com -u /status.shtml}


@subsubsection Result Example - IMPERIAL

     @itemize @bullet
	 @item
	 Returns CRITICAL if temperature is above 90F or humidity is below 10%.
	 @item
	 Returns WARNING if temperature is above 70F or humidity is below 5.
	 @item
	 Returns OK if temperature is 70F or below.
	 @item
	 Returns UNKNOWN if no response received within 60 seconds.
	 @end itemize

@subsubsection Syntax Example - METRIC

@emph{check_ubicom -m -wt 0:30 --critical-temperature=-10:50 -I example.remote-mon.com -u /status.shtml}

@subsubsection Result Example - METRIC

     @itemize @bullet
	 @item
	 Returns CRITICAL if temperature is below -10C or above 50C.
	 @item
	 Returns WARNING if temperature is below 0C or above 30C.
	 @item
	 Returns OK if temperature is from 0C to 30C.
	 @item
	 Returns UNKNOWN if no response received within 10 seconds.
	 @end itemize

@subsubsection Syntax Example - Macro
define command@{

        command_name    check_ubicom_whatever
		
        command_line    $USER1$/check_ubicom -I 10.10.10.22 -p 8264
		
@}

@subsection Weather Plugin - check_weather
The check_weather plugin checks the windchill, windspeed, humidity, pressure, and temperature received from @uref{http://developer.yahoo.com/weather/,Yahoo! Weather RSS Feed} for a single station code.  The return value is always OK or UNKNOWN.

You are certainly free to use any other RSS feed you prefer.  Examples of this include @uref{http://portal.theweatherchannel.com/,The Weather Channel} and @uref{http://www.wunderground.com/weather/api/,Weather Underground}.  All of these RSS feeds have free and paid options.  Please carefully read their provisions if you select to use their RSS feed.

The performance values returned by the check_weather plugin, @strong{in order}, are:
@enumerate
@item
wind chill (apparent temperature) in degrees F or degrees C
@item
wind speed in m.p.h. or km.p.h.
@item
relative humidity in percent
@item
barometric pressure in in.Hg or mm.Hg
@item
current temperature in degrees F or degrees C
@end enumerate

@subsubsection Syntax Example - IMPERIAL
@emph{check_weather -z USTN0268}

@subsubsection Result Example - IMPERIAL
OK|52 8 88 29.68 52

@enumerate
@item
52 degrees Fahrenheit windchill
@item
8 mph wind speed
@item
88% relative humidity
@item
29.7 in.Hg barometric pressure
@item
52 degrees Fahrenheit actual temperature
@end enumerate

@subsubsection Syntax Example - METRIC
@emph{check_weather -z USTN0268 -m}

@subsubsection Result Example - METRIC
OK|35 12.8748 88 753.872 35

@enumerate
@item
35 degrees Celsius windchill temperature
@item
12.8 km/h wind speed
@item
88% relative humidity
@item
758.8 mm.Hg barometric pressure
@item
35 degrees Celsius actual temperature
@end enumerate

@subsubsection Syntax Example - Macro
define command@{

        command_name    check_weather_knox
		
        command_line    $USER1$/check_weather -z USTN0268
		
@}

