@section Cabling 101
@subsection  Introduction

The intent of this writing is @strong{not} to make you an expert in cabling.  The intent is to provide you with the necessary reference information, tips, and recommendations for you to wisely use cabling.  There is no, repeat....no substitute for hands on experience with cabling.

Please carefully read all of this information before you attempt your cabling efforts.  Experience is a great teacher, so don't be afraid or discouraged if you mix up wiring patterns or do not terminate a connection well enough through the proper amount of pressure on a wire termination in the beginning of your cabling efforts.

@subsection  Cable
@uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category_5_cable,Category 5 cable} comes in many forms.  The cable is solid core 24-@uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_wire_gauge,AWG}.  8 separately jacketed wires, twisted in pairs, making 4 pairs all contained within a protective jacket.  The jacket that wraps around that cable is either @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plenum_cable,Plenum} or Non-Plenum.  Plenum cable is rated for a fire hazard area.  Category 5 cabling is often rated as @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low_voltage,low-voltage}, meaning you do not need a license to install the cable.  Please contact your local fire authority for more information.  

@subsection  Grounding
Proper cable grounding is essential for safety.  The assumption that the cable carries a low-voltage is true, but it also carries enough capability to damage the equipment connected together via your cable and you...the cabling person.  The differences between @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surge_suppression,surge-suppression} and @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transient-voltage-suppression_diode,transient-voltage-suppression} cannot be stated enough.  Please contact your local fire authority for more information.

@subsection  Installation
Category 5 cable is installed in either @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_conduit,electrical conduit}, @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cable_tray,cable trays}, or @uref{https://www.google.com/search?q=j-hooks,J-Hooks}.  Cable must, must, must be properly supported so as to not stretch the copper wire and cause for minor breaks in the wire.  Minor wire breaks cause for performance issues in @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quality_of_service,quality-of-service}, and lead to a breakage in one or more wires.  Cable is laid out in a pattern of either a @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_distribution_frame,main distribution frame} or an @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intermediate_distribution_frame,intermediate distribution frame}.

@subsection  Termination
Properly installed cable is then connected with some type of @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Registered_jack,registered jack/plug}.  This end result is called a cable termination.

@subsection  Testing
All cabling must have @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuity_test,continuity} all of the time.  A simple @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cable_tester,cable tester} is probably the most manageable @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuity_tester,continuity tester} there is after cable has been terminated with a registered jack/plug in order to determine if you have continuity.  If all else fails, connecting 2 bare wires together with a @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wire_nut,wire nut} on one end, then testing the other ends with a @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multimeter,multi-meter} is always an option.  This is quite valuable after cable has been laid in place and you want to know if it has continuity before terminating the cable.

@subsection  Usage Notes
	@itemize @bullet
	@item
	Your continuity tester will help you see when you have the proper wiring pattern and the proper amount of pressure on a wire termination.
	@item
	Pull some extra cable, loop it in a circle, and wire tie the cable loop together.  That provides for moving terminated cable if the future necessitates that, and has extra cable available for if you should mix up things when you terminate the cable.
	@item
	Don't make the diameter of your loop too small.  A 3-inch diameter cable loop results in nothing more than broken cable.  The same goes for when you install your cable and make a 90-degree turn.  Make you loop a good 9-inches in diameter at least.
	@item
	The satisfaction from installing your own cable is great, indeed.  The cost of installing your own cable is sometimes best paid for through a cabling company.  Count the cost and choose either your own labor or that of a cabling company that best suits you.
	@end itemize

@subsection  Cautionary
Whatever you do, always install your cable as required by your fire authority and always, always, always properly support your cable with either electrical conduit, cable trays, or J-Hooks.  Suffice it to say, cable that is not properly supported will eventually have small cracks in the wire, resulting in a quality-of-service loss, progressing to intermittent continuity problems, and ultimately completely break the wire somewhere within the cable jacket.

@section Power over Ethernet (PoE) 101
@subsection Introduction
@uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_over_Ethernet,Power over Ethernet} is quite possibly the best thing to come along to the Information Technology world of hardware since the 1980's.  Literally, it is that wonderful!  The essence of PoE is you can use @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category_5_cable,Category 5 cable,cable} that is rated as @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low_voltage,low-voltage} to power a multitude of PoE hardware @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_over_Ethernet#Uses,uses}.  The list of what is capable of PoE is constantly growing.  For starters, here are some common terms to understand.

@subsection Power Sourcing Equipment
The @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_over_Ethernet#Power_sourcing_equipment,PSE} is the network PoE element that inserts power onto a Category 5 cable. It may be an endspan device, such as a PoE-enabled data network switch, or a midspan device located between the data network switch and the PD.

@subsection Powered Device
A @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_over_Ethernet#Powered_device,PD} is the PoE capable device that receives power over Category 5 cable. It could be a PoE-enabled IP telephone, a Wireless Access Point, an IP enabled HVAC thermostat, any other IP device that requires electrical power.

@subsection Midspan
A midspan device is a PSE that inserts power onto the Category 5 cable. It is situated between the data network switch and the PD. Typically, midspan devices are added to existing networks to allow the use of PoE-enabled PD's.

@subsection Endspan
An endspan device is typically a data network switch that incorporates PoE capabilities. Endspan devices often are implemented when a new network is created, to avoid adding midspan devices as well as the switch.

@subsection  Usage Notes
Now, should you need/want to move a device such as a Wireless Access Point, an IP telephone, or an HVAC sensor to another location.....image how nice it would be to not have to juggle the powering of that device as well.  There are many @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_over_Ethernet#Powering_devices,combination} options available for PoE capable hardware.

Pressing onward, imagine a device is locked up and you need to power the device off and then turn it back on.  Walking to that device could very well be a hassle, and could involve opening a lot of access panels.  Using PoE, you can turn off the power over your data network and then turn it back on.

The thing for you with PoE is you need to determine how much electrical power you need.  That will tell you what specification you need to comply with.  The manufacturer of the PoE device will tell you what standards they are compatible with.  From there, buy PoE supplies as necessary.  Your selection is either a simple single-port power injector (Midspan), or a @uref{http://www2.microsemi.com/PowerDsine/Products/Midspan/,rack-mounted} midspan power injector , or buy new data network switches that have PoE built-in as an integrated feature (Endspan).  Count the cost and choose as best suits you.

The biggest benefit of PoE is you have the ability to have a better handle on your @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surge_suppression,surge-suppression} and @uref{http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transient-voltage-suppression_diode,transient-voltage-suppression} efforts.  This is because you so chose to install your cabling as recommended.  Running a wire as an extension off of an HVAC unit, or a wall outlet, in order to supply electricity to power the PoE capable hardware, without also providing proper protection for that PoE hardware, is absolutely and positively nothing but trouble.  That trouble often shows up as electrical damage in the form of peculiar performance of the hardware, or even hardware failure.

@subsection  Cautionary
Here is a strong and very simple example of why powering your IP enabled thermostat from an HVAC unit is a bad idea.  The drain line on the HVAC unit some how gets blocked.  This triggers the float switch to prevent flooding and that powers down the whole system.  The thermostat has then been turned off due to the absence of power to the thermostat.  Apply that scenario to an IP enabled thermostat, and your will be unable to access your HVAC unit from your data network.  Power over Ethernet is a really good idea.

Whatever you do, always use cable safely.  Please contact your local fire authority for more information.

